    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1953-06-10T01:22:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1953-06-10T01:22:00-05:00" n="589"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d589">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">
                    <persName corresp="#p_MHF1">Matthews</persName> files, lot 53 D 413:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Commander in Chief Far East (<persName corresp="#p_CGMW1"
                            type="from">Clark</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Joint Chiefs of
                            Staff</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d589fn1">This telegram was sent to <persName
                            corresp="#p_BEO1">Briggs</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_TLGMD1"
                            >Taylor</persName> for their exclusive information.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret<lb/>priority</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1953-06-10T15:22:00+09:00"
                            >June 10, 1953—3:22 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>CX 62966. Ref: A. <gloss target="#t_G1">G</gloss> 5812 KCG.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d589fn2">Dated June 9, <ref target="#pg_1159">p. 1159</ref>.</note>
                    B. GX 5817 KSG.<note n="3" xml:id="d589fn3">Dated June 9, <ref target="#pg_1161"
                            >p. 1161</ref>.</note> C. CX 62890.<note n="4" xml:id="d589fn4">Dated
                        June 7, <ref target="frus1952-54v15p1#pg_1149">p. 1149</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>
                        <persName corresp="#p_TLGMD1">Taylor</persName> conferred with <persName
                            corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> yesterday and submitted to me a rept of
                        his conversation, the details of which are contained in ref A. Subsequently
                            <persName corresp="#p_TLGMD1">Taylor</persName> discussed his meeting
                        with <persName corresp="#p_BEO1">Briggs</persName>, whose comments to me are
                        in ref B.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>I have nothing to add to either <persName corresp="#p_TLGMD1"
                            >Taylor</persName>’s or <persName corresp="#p_BEO1">Briggs</persName>’
                        obsrs other than to repeat that it is my conviction <persName
                            corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> has been, and is still, convinced of
                        the inevitability of an armistice agreement. There has been no material
                        change in <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName>’s attitude as reptd in
                        ref C.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Pub statements from <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> ofls and pressure
                        groups continue to oppose an armistice, demand the release of Korean
                        non-repatriate <gloss target="#t_POWs1">POWs</gloss> and threaten the use of
                        mil force against Communist elements and Indian armed forces who attempt to
                        enter South Korea. <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> is trying to
                        balance the advantages of a mutual security treaty with all of its attendant
                        benefits against the bitterness he feels personally and officially about the
                        non-unification of Korea and the apparent transgressions against <gloss
                            target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> sovereignty. The longer we delay an
                        armistice agreement, the longer he is subject to doubts and apprehensions
                        about his own psn, and it is for this reason that I feel we must push to an
                            <pb facs="0046" n="1164" xml:id="pg_1164"/> agreement as quickly as
                        possible to reduce the time <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> is
                        exposed to conflicting influences.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>I feel that <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> fully recognizes
                        the cold facts of the situation and the reasonableness of the steps the US
                        is willing to take in <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss> behalf as set
                        forth in Pres <persName corresp="#p_EDD1">Eisenhower</persName>’s ltr of 6
                            Jun.<note n="5" xml:id="d589fn5">Not printed, but see footnote 1, <ref
                                target="frus1952-54v15p1#pg_1148">p. 1148</ref>.</note> In my
                        opinion, <persName corresp="#p_RS1">Rhee</persName> sees the reality of an
                        armistice coming closer and closer. Our hope is that his bluffing will begin
                        to dissipate and, as we move to actual signing of the armistice, his true
                        intentions will be more clearly revealed. We must wait and see. I will watch
                        developments closely and keep you informed.</item>
                </list>
            </div>
